<br>
<br>
<DIV class="poemtitle">Postcard</DIV><br>
<TABLE><TR><TD>
<br /> 
<i>It’s hard to dream</i>, you write,<br /> 
<i>of a white Christmas on this bus ride <br /> 
through the jungle of Central Africa.</i><br /> 
It’s hard not to think as I read these lines   <br /> 
that the beauty of this unpeopled landscape<br />  
of fog and trees holds some undeciphered code.  <br /> 
Paradise paired with sentence fragments<br /> 
is how we communicate.  <br /> 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not say, <br /> 
<i>the vice-director has accused me <br /> 
of lying;  Jamal’s husband has committed suicide, <br /> 
my house has burned to the ground.</i><br /> 
These are for hiding in the folds of envelopes.  <br />   
<br /> 
Instead we seek comfort, we say: <br /> 
the glassy seascapes of Zanzibar<br /> 
will take your breath away,<br /> 
the budding minarets of Budapest <br /> 
are something to behold. Look carefully,<br /> 
your Italian lover should be somewhere <br /> 
in this picture, waiting for you.<br /> 
These words fill us: <br /> 
A thousand houses extend <br /> 
like bullet holes in the mountainside <br /> 
over the sea.    <br /> 
 

<br><br>

